content:
@sksq96 mostly: 1. much clearer sense of myself - my interests, my moods, thoughts, emotions, patterns, loops, traps, ups and downs, etc 

2, confidence in using words for thinking; in being able to make sense of my experiences, the world around me, how anything relates to anything else

it's interesting to consider contrapoints' latest video about envy

think about the idea that names have power

it's a very american thing i think to want everyone to know your name (not saying all americans want this, but ppl worldwide go to the us to "make it big") https://t.co/ewftzdhzk1

there's this interesting class of person who invests a remarkable amount of effort into telling everybody else that nothing is worth doing. the volunteer corps of the status quo. when they trap you in their pincers, it's easy (for me) to get ensnared in hours of arguments

@roberthaisfield just some of my general favs:

everything is a remix
wrestling isn’t wrestling
sequelitis megaman x
contrapoints (whatever seems interesting)

leonardo da vinci very narrowly avoided the prestige trap, because he was born out of wedlock

i wonder how many would've-been leonardos become investment bankers every year

 https://t.co/y5w2yyxhth

while plotting out my youtube strategy, i find myself thinking that i intend to embody a position that's sort of a mashup of both contrapoints and jordan peterson. this will either turn out quite interesting, or i will be pelted with rocks by everybody from all sides. fun

@jasoncrawford fdic insurance works a lot better, since the us had systemic banking crises every 12-20 years.

where’s my kindle; it’s a great book.
"hey we have this new idea for a business model. it's called a 'credit card.' we'll bootstrap by giving one to every person in los angeles."

of course, we always knew (tm) this was a broader banking crisis downstream primarily of rate hikes, requiring a systemic solution, which is why no one confidently blamed it on firms noticing the crisis and responding to it early. how could they have been early? we always knew.

note that internal sentiment seems to be “we did everything right. it was everyone else in the industry who effed up. if you were grading on a curve we deserve at least a b!”

this is why banking crises become crises; systemic risk and contagion turns b into bankrupt.

and a truly surprising number of technologists of my acquaintance learned everything they know about investment banking from the scenes designed to make investment bankers look like incompetent / corrupt actors.
rt @feikhal: interesting, i was always told that msg could cause anywhere from brain damage to miscarriages. turns out that's just systemic…
